{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_018Kuc3tWfMiukuZgTcYCSvi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture:\n\n1. The health check script reads a password from:\n   - `/etc/health/overrides/${POD_NAME}` (if exists) — mounted from `health-overrides` ConfigMap\n   - Otherwise `/etc/health/health-password` — mounted from `health-user-password` secret\n\n2. For `mongodb-replica-1`, there's an override in the `health-overrides` ConfigMap: `mongodb-replica-1: legacyHealthPass123`\n\n3. The secret `health-user-password` has password `healthpass123` (base64 decoded from `aGVhbHRocGFzczEyMw==`)\n   \n4. The authentication failure \"SCRAM authentication failed, storedKey mismatch\" on `mongodb-replica-1` reveals the mismatch: the health check is using `legacyHealthPass123` from the override, but the MongoDB server has `health-user` configured with `healthpass123`.\n\nSince credentials replicate across the replica set from the primary, all members including `mongodb-replica-1` have the same `health-user:healthpass123` combination. The override is causing the health check to authenticate with the wrong password.\n\nThe solution is either to remove the override for `mongodb-replica-1` so it uses the correct password from the secret, or update the MongoDB user password to match what the override specifies. Option A is cleaner—I'll remove the `mongodb-replica-1` override from the ConfigMap so the health check falls back to the correct password from the secret. Let me verify that `healthpass123` actually works on that pod before making the change.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1501,"cache_read_input_tokens":38302,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1501},"output_tokens":34,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostic